<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: MoD cash details revamped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBERS of soldiers, air force officers, tanks and frigates deployed on
particular commitments will be among the details given for the first time in
the annual statement on defence spending.
The revamped format for the white paper, which Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the
defence secretary, is to publish early next month, will identify individual
tasks, set out the manpower and equipment resources allocated to them, and
give a clearer idea of the costs of the operations.
The stated aim is to widen the public debate on defence spending beyond a
handful of specialists, but the new way of presenting information will also
help the ministry of defence in its negotiations with the Treasury during
the public spending round.
Because of 'double-hatting' - resources used to fulfil more than one
commitment - the total cost of all the individual tasks will be far higher
than the total defence budget, reinforcing the MOD's arguments about value
for money.
Ministers believe also that the armed forces command such 'affection and
respect' from the British public, that the MOD can only gain from bringing
greater openness and transparency to the defence accounts.
There was initially some resistance from officials and the military, but
they have now been convinced of the benefits. The revised approach will
combine information which had formerly been published piecemeal or only in
response to questions, with some material that has not previously been
available.
'The Russians had this information but the British didn't,' one minister
said yesterday.
It also has the advantage of containing in a single statement details of
equipment projects which have been cancelled, scaled back or delayed, thus
enabling the MOD to avoid several successive 'bad news' announcements.
</TEXT>
