<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour rounds on PM over Iraq probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR YESTERDAY accused Mr John Major of trying to 'bring down the
shutters' on the arms-for-Iraq affair, as it launched its strongest attack
yet on the government's refusal to answer questions on the subject, David
Owen writes.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, charged the prime
minister with betraying promises made when the Scott inquiry was set up.
'This is the arrogance of a government that has been in power so long that
it has forgotten it is accountable to parliament,' he said.
Mr Cook's comments followed a written answer by Mr Major in which he turned
down a request to make it government policy to give substantive replies to
parliamentary questions on arms-for-Iraq.
'These issues are being investigated by Lord Justice Scott, and it would be
wrong for the government to comment on them before publication of his final
report,' Mr Major said.
The government was 'making all the relevant facts available to the inquiry,
and it is right that we should wait for Lord Justice Scott to present his
conclusions before commenting publicly.'
</TEXT>
