<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Two-week extension for Swan Hunter frigate work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SWAN HUNTER, the Tyneside shipbuilder, has won a further two weeks'
outfitting work on the three Type 23 frigates which are its main workload,
Price Waterhouse, the yard's receivers, confirmed yesterday.
The agreement between the receivers and the Ministry of Defence is the third
temporary extension to work on the frigates since Swans went into
receivership in mid-May, after failing to win a crucial helicopter carrier
order.
Price Waterhouse said the extension until June 28 meant there would be no
redundancies in the coming fortnight among the remaining 2,000 employees.
Union leaders expressed concern at the effect of the agreement on morale. Mr
John Macciocchi, fitters' shop steward, said: 'We hope the MoD make a final
decision that Swans can finish these ships, then we can get down to business
and boost morale a little bit.'
Negotiations on whether Swans can complete the frigates, providing some work
until late 1994, are continuing. The Ministry of Defence said it was a very
complicated issue, adding: 'They must be completed within the time-frame and
the financial constraints.'
Completing the frigates would give Swans a chance of securing further orders
and being sold as a going concern.
The company's strongest hope for new work, a Pounds 40m patrol boats order
from the Royal Navy of Oman, hinges on satisfying the navy that its Pounds
8m advance payment would not be at risk.
The Department of Trade and Industry said yesterday it was still studying
whether it could underwrite the Pounds 8m as part of a total Pounds 20m
package of performance guarantees.
The department said the proposal, from local authorities and the Tyne and
Wear Development Corporation, raised technical and ideological questions.
The European Commission is still considering a government request to look
again at the exemption of UK warship yards, including Swans, from
Shipbuilding Intervention Fund eligibility.
The GMB general union, holding its annual congress in Portsmouth yesterday,
unanimously backed an emergency motion pledging full support for the Swans
workforce in its fight to complete the frigates.
</TEXT>
