<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Edinburgh to top British growth table
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH will be the fastest growing of Britain's big cities in the 1990s,
while economic activity in London will be held back by a fragile
manufacturing base, traffic jams and a contraction in business services, a
report published today predicts.
The European Economic Research and Advisory Consortium, a group of European
research institutes, says that out of 32 European cities, five of the bottom
eight ranked according to their 1990s growth potential are in Britain.
Edinburgh occupies a respectable 14th position, but London manages only a
poor 28th. Manchester and Birmingham are at the bottom of the league table,
and Glasgow and Cardiff rank 25th and 27th respectively.
Frankfurt, Paris and Amsterdam - rivals to London as centres for financial
services - rank higher at 11th, 12th and 13th.
London scores highly as a centre for banking and investment and as a
headquarters for multinational companies, but its growth potential may be
constrained by poor transport links and failure by the UK to participate
fully in European economic integration.
The UK economy as a whole is expected to grow relatively quickly in the next
year or so compared with other parts of Europe, but many big British cities
will continue the trend of the past 30 years and lose out economically in
relation to the countryside or suburbs.
Of the 32 cities Barcelona, Dublin, Lisbon, Berlin and Hamburg come out with
the highest ratings for likely economic growth.
Barcelona is considered capable of average growth of 3.4 per cent a year up
to 1997, but London is likely to achieve a comparable figure of just 1.2 per
cent.
Other also-rans in the bottom eight of the league table include Turin,
Dusseldorf and Cologne.
The report says that the declining share of manufacturing activity in the
economies of many big UK cities during the 1980s is a pivotal reason for
their relatively low growth prospects.
The Ereco members include Cambridge Econometrics from the UK, BIPE (Paris),
Ecotec (Birmingham), IFO (Munich), NEI (Rotterdam), Prometeia (Bologne) and
Wifo (Vienna).
European Regional Prospects, May 1993, European Economic Research and
Advisory Consortium. Cambridge Econometrics, Covent Garden, Cambridge CB1
2HS, or Ereco, 48 rue de Cardinal, 1040 Brussels. Two volume report for Ecu
2,000 or Pounds 1,600.
