<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Radio groups plan business news station
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO RIVAL consortia hoping to launch commercial business radio stations for
the London area were among 48 applications submitted to the Radio Authority
yesterday.
The applications were for eight commercial licences for the capital, six of
which are already held by existing broadcasters.
The competition for a business station on an AM frequency pitches London
Business Radio (LBR) - whose shareholders are the GWR radio group, Reuters
and Associated Newspapers - against London City Talk Radio.
City Talk has been put together by Mr Mike Bloomberg, the Wall Street
entrepreneur who is a growing rival of Reuters in the financial information
business. Mr Bloomberg's backers include the International Herald Tribune
newspaper and Professor George Bain, principal of the London Business
School.
LBR would draw on the strength of Reuters correspondents around the world.
City Talk would aim to be the radio equivalent of US-based television
service Cable News Network, with 20-minute programme segments updated 24
hours a day.
Among the other radio licence applications submitted yesterday there were
two rivals for services aimed mainly at women listeners: Radio Viva and
London AM.
Five groups want to provide services on both AM and FM. Those applications
came from the Chrysalis group, Allied Radio, London Broadcasting Company,
London News Radio (backed by merchant bank Guinness Mahon), and LBR.
Other offerings included two country music applications, two sports
services, and an application from London Transport for a travel and
travel-related service.
Sixteen applications were submitted for ethnic services in the capital.
The Radio Authority, the industry regulator, is expected to make its
decisions on this round of licence applications in the next three months.
In the past the authority has re-awarded the commercial licences but, this
time, the heavy number of applicants for the London area could lead to
casualties among the existing companies.
Apart from LBC, which yesterday appointed broadcaster Mr David Dimbleby as a
non-executive director, those defending existing licences are Jazz FM, Kiss
FM, Melody Radio and Spectrum International Radio.
</TEXT>
