<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Sharp rise in higher education intake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STUDENT numbers in English higher education have risen by 46 per cent in the
past four years, says the first annual report of the Higher Education
Funding Council.
The council said this expansion, which exceeded the government's own
forecasts, had been achieved 'while maintaining quality and strengthening
research activities'. Professor Graeme Davies, chief executive, said the
increase was equivalent to the creation of 20 large civic universities.
The report shows that the composition of the student body is changing, with
far more mature students. Those over 21 now take up the majority of higher
education places, accounting for 55 per cent of all students, while 38 per
cent of all students are 35 or older.
Ethnic minorities are well represented relative to their share of the
population, accounting for 13 per cent of UK-based students. Only 8 per cent
of the population aged between 18 and 29 came from ethnic minorities in
1991, says the report.
Promoting Quality and Opportunity. HEFC, Northavon House, Coldharbour Lane,
Bristol BS16 1QD.
