<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Haiti's Prime Minister resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Haiti's Prime Minister Marc Bazin resigned yesterday, creating a dangerous
power vacuum in the troubled Caribbean nation whose military refuses to
restore democracy despite the threat of increased sanctions, Reuter reports
from Port-au-Prince.
In Managua, Nicaragua, where the Organisation of American States is
discussing how to step up the pressure, ousted President Jean Bertrand
Aristide said he hoped the news could mean his return to Haiti 'within the
next few weeks or even days'.
Mr Bazin, a former World Bank economist, quit after he had been prevented
from appointing four new cabinet members.
Political pressure had been mounting since Friday when four ministers, some
with links to the police chief of Port-au-Prince, had refused to step down.
Mr Bazin had also lost the support of a small centrist party which had given
him a parliamentary majority.
</TEXT>
