<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Law firm's advice to trustees raises doubt on pension rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PLENDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PENSION fund trustees defending a High Court action brought by the
Securities and Investments Board were advised by a leading law firm that it
was 'almost impossible to pursue a trustee for negligence when it comes to
investment'.
The advice raises questions about the effectiveness of the UK regulatory
framework for pensions, as the government-appointed Goode Committee prepares
its review of pensions law.
The advice, contained in a letter from Mr John Quarrell, a partner in the
West End firm of Nabarro Nathanson, to Melton Medes Pension Trustees,
related to a transaction that led to large losses for the pension fund.
The letter was written in September 1991 after seven employees of Melton
Medes, an unquoted Midlands-based conglomerate, had approached a leading QC
for advice. The letter said: 'You really have to have your fingers in the
till and it must be clearly shown that whilst they are in there they are
purloining large amounts of money, before anyone can bring a likely
successful action.'
Asked to comment on the advice, Melton Medes said questions should be
directed to solicitor DJ Freeman. Mr Marcus Rutherford, a partner in the
firm, said in the light of legal proceedings over the fund 'it would be
inappropriate to comment'.
The trustees had approved a loan of Pounds 4m from two pension funds in the
Melton Medes group to the parent company at uncommercial interest rates. The
loan was repaid in shares in two small quoted companies in which Melton
Medes and Mr Nathu Ram Puri, its chairman, had large stakes. The pension
funds suffered when both companies' share prices fell. The SIB's High Court
writ asks Mr Puri and the trustees for Pounds 691,681, plus interest, to be
restored to the pension funds, or such sum as the court sees fit.
Mr Puri and the pension fund trustees are also the subject of legal
proceedings in the High Court brought by seven employees. They have asked
the court to permit the release of funds from the pension scheme to finance
an action challenging the validity of the trust deeds.
A question of trust, Page 20
</TEXT>
