<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Macedonia wool suits fuel US ire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US TEXTILE and apparel importers have attacked as 'insanity' a new US quota
to limit the importing of wool suits from Macedonia to 80,000 a year,
cutting the present level by about one fifth, Nancy Dunne writes from
Washington.
The decision, by the government's Committee for the Implementation of
Textile Agreements, was 'another example of the business-as-usual attitude
pervading the US textile programme,' said Ms Laura Jones, executive director
of the US Association of Importers of Textiles and Apparel.
'Is this Macedonia's reward for enforcing the UN's trade sanctions against
Serbia, its largest trading partner?' she asked.
The US has been gradually imposing textile and clothing quotas on most
eastern European economies, despite a stated US policy of helping their
development by increasing trade.
</TEXT>
