<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Trafalgar rights fear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Volume in international conglomerate Trafalgar House rose to a hefty 12m,
making it the day's most heavily traded stock and the shares gave up 4 to
106p as fears that the company would soon be calling on investors for more
cash swept through the market.
Speculation of a rights issue was fuelled by reports in the weekend press
and by the close of business yesterday a feeling that a cash call was
inevitable had grown. One analyst said: 'The balance sheet is still
stretched and I just cannot see how they can avoid one.' However, Mr Geoff
Allum at NatWest Securities said: 'It will be difficult for them to get a
rights issue away. I think it is more likely that Trafalgar will attempt
disposals.'
Such a move would be the third time in less than two years that Trafalgar
had called on the market, having raised Pounds 204m in February this year
through a sterling issue and Pounds 310m through a rights issue in July
1991.
