<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Money Markets: French rates unchanged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEALERS in French franc interest rate markets were bullish yesterday about
the prospect of further policy easing by the Bank of France, even though the
authorities left official interest rates unchanged, writes James Blitz.
The French franc has performed strongly against the D-Mark on the currency
markets in recent days, and there was speculation about another cut in the
Bank of France's intervention rate, currently at 7.50 per cent. In the
event, this interest rate was left unaltered in the central bank's weekly
operation.
However, the currency's strength raised speculation that the French
authorities would be able to reduce interest rates at a more aggressive pace
than has been set by the Germans. French franc interest rate futures were
yesterday discounting lower interest rates in France than in Germany in June
and September.
French cash rates have been below their German counter-parts for several
weeks. But this is only the second day on which the trend has emerged in
futures markets.
The June French franc contract closed 7 basis points higher at 92.54, while
the September contract was up 12 basis points on the day at 93.32.
Euromark futures were only mildly stronger. The June D-Mark interest rate
contract ended at 92.45, up 2 basis points on the day. The September
contract finished 2 basis points firmer at 93.23.
The weaker rise in German interest rate contracts was partly due to the
perception that the D-Mark was losing ground across the board on the
currency markets, and that this would make German rate cuts more difficult
to implement.
However, D-Mark weakness allowed the Danish authorities to cut rates for the
first time since Denmark voted Yes to monetary union on May 18. Denmark's
discount rate was lowered from 8.25 per cent to 7.75 per cent.
Dealers in sterling markets took a more downbeat view of interest rate cuts,
following press reports that the UK government was shying away from any more
easing.
The September short sterling contract closed 7 basis points down at 94.19.
Three-month money finished slightly firmer at 5 15/16 per cent, following
difficulties removing a Pounds 1bn shortage.
