<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / International Company News: Klockner write-off plan approved
by creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KLOCKNER-WERKE, the ailing German steel producer, yesterday won overwhelming
approval from its creditors for a debt relief scheme, paving the way for the
company to write off nearly 50 per cent of its DM2.7bn (Dollars 1.66m) debt.
Creditors, dominated by the leading German banks, will receive between 40
and 60 per cent of their claims. Small creditors, owed no more than
DM10,000, will be fully reimbursed.
The approval also leaves Klockner free to reopen negotiations for the sale
of a significant share of its steel assets, a company spokesman said.
The company is considering selling at least a 50 per cent stake to an
outsider, Mr Hans Christoph von Rohr, Klockner's chairman, told the
Frankfurter Allgemeine newspaper yesterday.
The sale of Klockner-Edelstahl, the special steel division, was announced
earlier this year pending the success of the debt-relief scheme.
The subsidiary is to be sold for a symbolic DM2 to Mr Jurgen Grossmann, its
chairman until February 15. Druker, a Frankfurt-based consultancy company,
will acquire 25 per cent of the shares.
Thyssen and Krupp-Hoesch, Germany's two largest steelmakers, also announced
last month that they would lead a European consortium of steel producers to
bid for Klockner's cold-rolling mill, the most profitable part of the
company.
But Mr von Rohr said he would not sell such an important asset without also
negotiating the sale of a part of Klockner's hot-rolling mill, an area of
the European industry which suffers from severe overcapacity.
Any move by Klockner to sell part its core steel assets will be watched with
some trepidation by other German steelmakers which have expressed worries at
the prospect of the company emerging better able to compete in a market
still affected by over-capacity.
Under pressure from other steel producers, including German steelmakers, the
European commission insisted on significant capacity cuts at Klockner before
agreeing to write-off part of its DM175m loan.
Under its agreement with the commission, signed last Friday, Klockner will
reduce its pig-iron capacity by 33 per cent to 2.4m tonnes per year. The
company's crude steel production will fall by 20 per cent to 2.8m while its
hot-rolling mill capacity will decrease by 12 per cent to 3.7m tonnes.
The company plans to tear down one of its two blast furnaces in Bremen in
answer to the EC demand that its production cuts be made irreversible.
Creditors will also be entitled, over the next 8 years, to receive a third
of the group's distributable profits, including earnings coming from its
non-steel divisions, as long as this does not make up more than 50 per cent
of the debt they have agreed to cancel.
The debt-relief plan is expected to be approved today and tomorrow by the
creditors of Klockner's steel subsidiaries, most of whom are the same as
those of the holding company.
</TEXT>
