<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Land Rover deal to sell in Japan under Honda banner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Land Rover Discovery, the successful UK-built four-wheel drive vehicle,
is to be sold under an alias in Japan as the Honda Crossroad in a move to
tempt Japan's domestically-biased new car buyers.
Rover said last night that the deal was 'unique in modern automotive
history, because it is the first time that a Japanese car manufacturer has
put its own badge on a foreign car for the Japanese market'.
Imports captured only 4 per cent of the Japanese car market last year.
Land Rover is to create 300 jobs at its Solihull plant in the UK to increase
Discovery production from 700 to 900 a week from September as a result of
the deal with Honda and to meet demand in some European markets, in
particular the UK. The workforce will rise to 8,400.
The plant should receive a further boost next year, when the Discovery is
scheduled to be launched in the US through the UK group's own distribution
network.
The Discovery was launched in Japan in 1991 through the Rover dealer
network, but the marketing agreement announced last night will give the UK
vehicle maker access to one of Honda's domestic sales channels and promises
to double Discovery sales in Japan. Honda is planning sales of more than
1,000 in the first year.
The deal marks a further step in the far-reaching alliance between Honda and
Rover. The Japanese carmaker already holds a 20 per cent equity stake in the
Rover vehicle operations, and a large part of the modern Rover car range is
based on Honda technology.
The Land Rover Discovery marketing deal for Japan is the first time that the
product flow has been reversed.
Honda lacks a presence in the fast-growing world market for four-wheel drive
leisure/utility vehicles, unlike its domestic rivals Toyota, Nissan, Isuzu
and Mitsubishi Motors.
For North America it reached agreement late last year with Isuzu to sell the
US-built Isuzu Rodeo four-wheel drive leisure/utility vehicle under the
Honda name.
The deal with Land Rover is aimed at filling the same gap in its product
range in its domestic market. Honda also imports the rival Jeep Cherokee
from the US, but for sale under the Jeep brand.
</TEXT>
