FT  08 JUN 93 / Clarke firm against early ERM re-entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday dismissed the prospect of early
British re-entry to the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary
System.
The British and German economies 'are so far out of line that the conditions
are not remotely there for Britain to rejoin the ERM', Mr Clarke said. The
chancellor's forthright remarks came during a day of negotiations in
Brussels with other EC finance ministers.
Making his first statements on policy since taking over from Mr Norman
Lamont as chancellor, Mr Clarke also said that tackling the British budget
deficit was 'one of the most important items on the agenda'.
He voiced concern at the depth of the German recession and the effect on its
European partners. Underlining the point, the EC commission delivered a grim
warning to ministers that economic recovery in the EC as whole was unlikely
before the second half of 1994.
The commission forecast that the UK economy would outperform its main
competitors, with growth of 1.7 per cent this year.
Mr Clarke put up a roadblock against Community plans for two controversial
taxes - the carbon energy tax and a tax on imports of works of art. Further
negotiations are expected on both taxes.
EC warns of poor recovery outlook, Page 2
