<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You never know, television may yet grow up. Usually documentaries on social
subjects reflect the politically correct view: Boo] to landowners and
non-socialist governments, Hooray] for the little people. It makes better
television. Today's Assignment considers projects for dams in India and Sri
Lanka of a sort normally considered to be among the best ways of providing
cheap electricity and water. We are told, however, that opponents say such
dams destroy the habitat of people and animals while the extra power and
water are often grabbed by rich farmers and industrialists. Usually this
would ensure the hostility of the documentary maker, yet the billing for
today's programme (7.45 BBC2) ends by asking 'But is the new orthodoxy as
doctrinaire and blinkered as the one it replaces?' This suggests a quite
abnormal maturity. BBC2 also puts together a fascinating sequence of
90-second opinion pieces shown some weeks ago in which all sorts of people
enthused over their favourite works of art. Together they make a 35-minute
programme, The Great Picture Trail (9.45).
</TEXT>
<XX>
