<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Bottomley faces Pounds 1m legal
claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government was yesterday faced with a Pounds 1m damages claim in the
latest stage of a legal tussle over restrictive practices in British medical
accreditation.
Dr Anthony Goldstein, a London rheumatologist, issued a High Court writ
against Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, claiming damages for loss
of earnings over the past 11 years. He claims that he has suffered
financially because of government failure to implement 1975 EC medical
directives properly.
Dr Goldstein has been active in a campaign against the UK government's
approach to the directives, which were designed to establish mutual
recognition of medical qualifications within the EC. Earlier this year he
argued successfully in the High Court that UK criteria for awarding
specialist medical accreditation breached the EC regulations, but failed to
win damages.
Although Dr Goldstein holds a European specialists' certificate - intended
to achieve the mutual recognition of qualifications - he argues that the UK
medical authorities have failed to give it full effect.
'This is essentially a Pounds 1m damages claim following a deliberate breach
of EC law by Britain since 1976,' he said yesterday.
In January a working party chaired by Dr Kenneth Calman, the government's
chief medical officer, acknowledged that Britain's system of specialist
accreditation, run by the medical royal colleges, had operated in tandem
with the EC scheme.
</TEXT>
