<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine denies wrongdoing over
Nadir
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, yesterday insisted
that he had done nothing wrong in raising the handling of the case of Mr
Asil Nadir, the bankrupt former chairman of Polly Peck, with Sir Nicholas
Lyell, the attorney-general.
His statement explaining how he had come to approach Sir Nicholas failed,
however, to prevent Labour stepping up its attack on the involvement of
ministers with the case of Mr Nadir, who jumped bail last month and fled to
northern Cyprus.
Opposition backbenchers demanded a Commons statement on the the actions of
Mr Michael Mates, a middle-ranking minister, who separately raised the
matter with Sir Nicholas, and gave Mr Nadir a 'light-hearted' gift of a
watch.
Downing Street said that in raising the matter as a constituency MP, Mr
Mates had acted 'in line with the guidance issued to ministers'. His
resignation had been neither offered nor sought.
Mr Heseltine said that after a lunch early this year with a personal friend,
Mr Christopher Morgan, one of Mr Nadir's public relations advisers, he had
mentioned his conversation to Sir Nicholas.
Sir Nicholas had advised him that any concerns should be put in writing so
that they could be properly considered. Mr Heseltine had passed this message
back to Mr Morgan, and had heard nothing more. 'My own view is absolutely
clear that what I did was right, and if I had done anything less it would
have been wrong,' Mr Heseltine said.
Although he had earlier been quoted as denying involvement in any approach
Mr Heseltine might have made, Mr Morgan said yesterday that he 'drew the
attention' of Mr Heseltine to Mr Nadir's position.
Mr Morgan said he had had an 'informal and confidential' meeting with Mr
Heseltine to express Mr Nadir's concerns at how his case was being pursued
by the Serious Fraud Office and the belief that he was being denied the
opportunity to prepare his defence properly.
Some Tory backbenchers remained uneasy about Mr Mates' judgment, and the
issue could be brought up at this Thursday's meeting of the 1922 committee
of Conservative MPs. But, unless further embarrasing revelations emerge, he
is expected to survive.
Labour intends to use the case to build up pressure on Sir Norman Fowler,
the Tory party chairman, who is due to appear next week at a cross-party
committee investigation into the funding of political parties.
Mr Mark Rogerson, Mr Morgan's partner and the constituent of Mr Mates, who
alerted him to Mr Nadir's position, said his public relations firm had not
yet been paid by Mr Nadir. He said he was aware that Mr Nadir was bankrupt.
'We worked for him on the basis that, when he had the ability to pay, he
would.'
</TEXT>
