<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith faces uphill struggle to
reform union links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 50 per cent of the total votes at the Labour party's annual conference
are now pitted against the plan by Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, to
modernise his party's links with trade unions.
Yesterday three of the largest unions, the GMB general union, Nupe, the
public-service union, and the NCU telecommunications union, all voted at
their annual conferences against Mr Smith's plans for one-member-one-vote in
the selection of parliamentary candidates.
Other big unions, holding their congresses in the next few weeks, are
expected to take similar stances in what is emerging as a bitter battle
between the big unions and the 'modernisers' in the Labour party.
Several options for reform have been suggested by the unions and there is
likely to be a tense negotiation within the movement for a compromise.
Mr John Edmonds, general-secretary of the GMB, said: 'The party faces two
very unattractive options. The first is that the issue goes to the
conference in the autumn, and the way that the votes seem to be going
indicates the party leader's proposals will go down. The second is we have
an unseemly public row that rattles on for weeks.'
Previously seen as a staunch supporter of Mr Smith, who is sponsored by the
GMB, Mr Edmonds has started a bandwagon which is set to roll until the
party's annual conference in the autumn. A leading moderate who has been
happy to portray the GMB as a 'loyalist' union, this is the first time he
has fallen out so strongly with Labour in public.
Mr Tom Sawyer, deputy general secretary of Nupe, meeting in Scarborough,
said his union's proposal was not one-member-one-vote and not the block
vote, but something that could be a bridge between the two through a
register of Labour party supporters.
The GMB's proposal is similar. It recommended yesterday that a reformed
electoral college be set up for the next round of elections of parliamentary
candidates as a transition towards the use of a register of people who paid
the political levy to the party.
A vote against one-member-one-vote will mean that there is no procedure for
the next round of candidate selections, which is due to start in January -
hence Mr Smith's desire to persuade the party conference to back his plans.
Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, later issued a statement saying
that yesterday's vote by the GMB 'exposes the sham of John Smith's Labour
party.
'The next few months will show that the Labour party is still a wholly-owned
subsidiary of the trade union movement.'
</TEXT>
