FT  08 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Unions deal blow to Smith plans for
voting reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS by Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, to modernise his party's links
with trade unions were snubbed yesterday as two of the largest unions voted
against them.
The GMB general union and Nupe, the public-service union, both voted at
their annual conferences against Mr Smith's plans for one-member-one-vote in
the selection of parliamentary candidates.
The NCU telecommunications union, holding its conference in Blackpool, is
also expected to vote against the plan which Mr Smith is determined to push
through.
About 50 per cent of the total votes at the Labour party's annual conference
are now already pitted against the reforming plan. Other big unions, holding
their congresses in the next few weeks, are expected to take similar stances
in what is emerging as a bitter battle between the big unions and the
'modernisers' in the Labour party.
Several options for reform have been suggested by the unions and there is
likely to be a tense negotiation within the movement for a compromise.
Mr John Edmonds, general-secretary of the GMB, told reporters: 'The party
faces two very unattractive options. The first is that the issue goes to the
conference in the autumn and the way that the votes seem to be going
indicates the party leader's proposals will go down. The second is we have
an unseemly public row that rattles on for a large number of weeks.'
He said the best possibility was that the review group, which examined the
relationship between the Labour party and trade unions, be recalled and that
it try to make a unanimous recommendation to the party's ruling national
executive committee in advance of the party conference.
Mr Tom Sawyer, deputy general secretary of NUPE, meeting in Scarborough,
said his union's proposal was not one-member-one-vote and not the block vote
 -but a register of Labour party supporters.
The GMB's proposal is similar. It recommended yesterday that a reformed
electoral college be set up for the next round of elections of parliamentary
candidates as a transition towards the use of a register of people who paid
the political levy to the Labour party.
A vote against one-member-one-vote will mean that there is no procedure for
the next round of candidate selections.
Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, later issued a statement saying
that yesterday's vote by the GMB 'exposes the sham of John Smith's Labour
party.
'The next few months will show that the Labour party is still a wholly-owned
subsidiary of the trade union movement.'
