<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Slash public spending, urges IoD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC RECOVERY could be crushed unless the government acts urgently to
eliminate up to Pounds 30bn of public sector debt, the Institute of
Directors said yesterday.
Calling for a 'revolutionary approach' to government spending, Mr Peter
Morgan, the institute's director-general, said the Pounds 50bn deficit was
so huge that 'no tax increases of acceptable proportions could come near to
dealing with it'.
He told Sussex businessmen that the scale and rate of growth of public
spending constituted the economy's most serious problem.
'If the chancellor allows the government to continue to spend around half of
the national income, and increases the tax burden to pay for it, then
enterprise, the process of wealth creation and economic growth will be
crushed,' he added.
He emphasised that raising taxes to cut the budget deficit would 'simply
guarantee that the ratchet of public expenditure would continue its upward
thrust'.
Mr Morgan claimed that Britain had been living beyond its means for years, a
fact disguised only by the proceeds of privatisation and the high level of
tax receipts during the 1980s.
Without reform, the welfare state would increasingly fail to meet the
demands and expectations that had been fostered by four decades of digging
more deeply into the public purse.
He urged the government to conduct a fundamental review of the public
service, encompassing its purpose, efficiency and staffing levels.
'Since the middle class at present both pay (for) and benefit from the
welfare state, any changes the government makes will affect them directly.
'It will be essential to win their support and convince them that their
interests will be better serviced by making personal provision and
exercising individual choice - and this means not increasing their taxes,'
Mr Morgan added.
He said the IoD would press the new chancellor, Mr Kenneth Clarke, to
encourage those capable of making private provision by allowing tax relief
on the cost of premiums and fees for welfare and health.
The belief that the recovery may be slowing down has been fuelled by the
first fall for a year in the Central Statistical Office's longer leading
index, which tracks the economy.
The index, which highlights turning points in economic activity about 11
months in advance, fell from 109.3 in March to 108.9 in April after several
months of upward movements. That confirms other indications that any upturn
is likely to be patchy.
</TEXT>
