<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Why Belfast-style precautions may be adopted in City:
Richard Evans on a local authority's rapid response to the threat of bombs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKERS and the business community have given a largely favourable response
to a proposal by the Corporation of London - the local authority for the
City - to bar non-essential traffic from the core of the City as an
anti-terrorist measure.
The plan, the most radical element in a security package now being drafted,
is still at the blueprint stage and will be subject to public consultation
later this month. If accepted, it could be in operation by the end of the
year.
Mr Michael Cassidy, chairman of the corporation's policy and resources
committee, said yesterday that two large terrorist bombs in 14 months had
not undermined the City as Europe's leading financial centre. But companies
had to be reassured.
'Pedestrianisation would help security significantly in that it would
restrict vehicle access to key areas. We take the threat of terrorism
seriously, and we have a clear message from a group of foreign banks that if
we did not act, the consequences could be severe,' Mr Cassidy said.
Corporation officials led by Sir Francis McWilliams, the Lord Mayor, have
held meetings with more than 400 City institutions and companies to discuss
improved security.
Most have supported a vehicle ban, although some have argued it would create
too much disruption and would give too great a propaganda coup to the IRA.
Mr Cassidy argued that, as more than 90 per cent of City workers commuted by
train and walked to offices, there was a lot of support for a car ban,
provided that public transport could be improved.
Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, chairman of the London Stock Exchange, has given
pedestrianisation qualified backing, provided access for vehicles could be
maintained for normal business purposes.
The restrictions planned by the corporation are likely to apply only to a
few hundred square yards at the heart of the City, covering the area around
the Bank of England, the Stock Exchange, Mansion House and the NatWest
Tower, although some bankers want them to cover the whole of the square
mile. Access would be limited to buses, taxis and a few specially licensed
vehicles, but temporary licences could be granted for anyone giving a good
reason for driving through the City. Any vehicles without a licence would be
stopped at one of about six check points.
The corporation began its detailed examination of security after the
Bishopsgate bomb in April, which was placed in an abandoned tipper truck. A
year ago 100lbs of explosives packed into a car wrecked the Baltic Exchange.
Both bombs caused millions of pounds of damage.
Anti-terrorist measures already in hand are the removal of all litter bins
in the City until they can be made bombproof, the recruitment of 57 extra
police to step up patrols, and an increase in the number of police
surveillance cameras.
However, it is the prospect of a City traffic ban that is certain to create
the most controversy, particularly in surrounding areas that may have to
cope with increased traffic congestion.
The Association of London Authorities said it was concerned at the impact a
traffic ban in the City would have on other parts of London, particularly
neighbouring boroughs such as Camden, Islington, Tower Hamlets and Hackney.
'It needs to be done on a London-wide basis and after consultation,' an ALA
official said.
Mr Cassidy said there would be widespread consultation before any scheme was
introduced, and details were being fed into computers over the next week to
see what the traffic impact might be on surrounding areas.
Tighter security measures of the type being considered by the corporation
have been applied for years in Belfast, but in the past year three big bombs
have struck the Ulster capital's business centre.
However, London's position as a major international financial centre is
putting heavy pressure on the authorities and police to devise a policy
based on deterrence a deterrent rather than containment. A third big bomb
attack could make some foreign companies think about relocating elsewhere in
Europe.
</TEXT>
