<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / TV advert joint ventures explored
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Television is talking to Granada Television and Meridian
Broadcasting, the new south of England ITV company, about possible joint
ventures in television airtime sales.
TVMM, the Scottish company's joint venture with HTV, the ITV company for
Wales and the West, also sells advertising for its northern neighbour
Grampian Television and for Westcountry.
Granada is also talking to Meridian, which decided to sell its own airtime
when it began broadcasting in January rather than join an existing sales
house.
A Granada link with TVMM or Meridian would take both up to a 25 per cent
share of ITV advertising - the maximum allowed under existing legislation.
It would also create a powerful sales force which could command television
advertising sales of about Pounds 400m a year.
The talks are taking place against growing tension in the commercial
television industry. Last month London Weekend Television paid Pounds 14m
for a 14 per cent stake in Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television.
The deal was accompanied by a five-year advertising sales contract under
which LWT will receive a fixed annual fee plus commission for selling the
Yorkshire group's advertising.
Granada was interested in the Yorkshire stake and was upset to be pipped to
the deal.
Mr Tim Wootton, managing director of TSMS, the largest sales house, pointed
out last night that in 1989 there were 14 separate sales points for ITV
advertising. There are now seven.
</TEXT>
