FT  08 JUN 93 / World Trade News: Top Thai committee to act on motorway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE THAI government has formed a high-level committee, headed by deputy
prime minister Amnuay Viranvan, to try to settle a dispute over the contract
terms of an almost completed Dollars 1bn (Pounds 640m) elevated motorway,
writes William Barnes in Bangkok.
The second stage of a toll road running through Bangkok remains closed
despite government demands that it open immediately because of 'a national
crisis' in the city's traffic system.
Bangkok Expressway - the consortium, led by Kumagai Gumi, which is building
the road - says it will open the road toll-free for 90 days if the
government agrees to settle the dispute within that time. It insists it will
terminate the contract if there is no agreement by then.
The state-owned Expressway and Rapid Transit Authority responsible for the
project has now effectively been cut out of negotiations and its governor
has offered to resign.
Meanwhile, Japan's Obayashi group has pulled out of building Bangkok's third
stage expressway.
