<TEXT>
LOS ANGELES residents go to the polls today to choose a mayor in a
neck-and-neck contest, as two candidates fight for different kinds of votes
in the same city.
Mr Michael Woo, a 41-year-old councilman and liberal Democrat who is the
grandson of Chinese immigrants, aims to become the first Asian-American
mayor of a big US city. But he faces a tight race against Mr Richard
Riordan, 62, a political newcomer and millionaire businessman who is a
conservative Republican.
The winner will succeed Mr Tom Bradley, a black liberal, who is retiring
after 20 years.
Mr Woo has won broad support from the large immigrant community in Los
Angeles and, at the weekend, his campaign focused on south central Los
Angeles, the site for the riots of last year. In contrast, Mr Riordan
appeals to more affluent suburban voters.
