<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Election of LA mayor wide open
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LOS ANGELES residents go to the polls today to choose a mayor in a
neck-and-neck contest as two candidates fight for different kinds of votes
in the same city.
Mr Michael Woo, a 41-year-old councilman and liberal Democrat who is the
grandson of Chinese immigrants, aims to become the first Asian-American
mayor of a big US city. But he faces a tight race against Mr Richard
Riordan, 62, a political newcomer and millionaire businessman who is a
conservative Republican.
The winner will succeed Mr Tom Bradley, a liberal Democrat and one of the
first black mayors in the US, who is retiring after 20 years.
Mr Woo has won broad support from the large immigrant community in Los
Angeles and, at the weekend, his campaign focused on south central Los
Angeles, the site for the riots of last year.
In contrast, Mr Riordan appeals to more affluent suburban voters. He made
one of his last campaign stops, over the weekend, in a San Fernando Valley
park where a two-year-old was shot to death during a gang-related incident
on Easter Sunday in April.
Mr Riordan - who says the top three campaign themes are 'safety, safety,
safety' - has pledged to put 3,000 more police officers on the streets with
a plan financed, in part, by leasing the city-owned Los Angeles
International Airport to a private group.
Mr Woo has won the endorsement of the Los Angeles Times, the city's leading
newspaper.
It said of him: 'In a city with a hundred different voices straining to be
heard - in a city with a lot of conflict and much too much bad feeling - he
is the better listener, and so the better conciliator. And in this
fragmented city, it is the better conciliator who'll get results.'
</TEXT>
