<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Attali to fight his corner on reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Jacques Attali, the beleaguered president of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, yesterday demonstrated his continued
determination to fight for his position by announcing that the bank's board
of directors would meet in the next few days to discuss plans for a
structural reorganisation.
Speaking to the American Chamber of Commerce in London, in his first public
speech since the bank held its annual meeting in April, Mr Attali refused to
give any details about his proposals for the reform, or confirm reports that
the reorganisation would leave him in overall charge of the bank, insisting
that 'there will be no announcement until the board has discussed and
decided'.
He did concede that 'the bank is growing and needs a better structure' and
indicated that restructuring of the organisation, which has grown to 600
people, was imminent.
The bank yesterday confirmed that Mr Attali had called the meeting for this
week, but denied that this had been in response to reports of an imminent
reshuffle or growing pressure on Mr Attali to resign in the wake of
controversy over the bank's spending on entertainment and travel.
The announcement of the reorganisation comes at a critical time for Mr
Attali, with an audit report on the EBRD's spending practices imminent and
the US congress nearing a final decision on whether to keep up the US's
contributions to the bank's capital.
But G7 officials, who have been pushing for the appointment of a new chief
executive officer - possibly Mr Ernest Stern, one of the three managing
directors of the World Bank - to take over management responsibilities from
Mr Attali, seem unlikely to be placated by the impending reorganisation.
Mr Attali yesterday refused to confirm reports that Mr Stern, was being
considered for a senior role - though he joked that non-Europeans like Mr
Stern were unlikely to be ever appointed president, since 'the president of
the bank has to be a citizen of one of the countries of the community'.
One aspect of any change might be to appoint a new person to act as the
bank's chief operating officer, leaving Mr Attali in charge of overall
strategy, but divorced from day-to-day administration.
In his speech, the French bank chief launched a vigorous defence of the
EBRD's record, which, he said, had had a '300 per cent' growth since it was
founded two years ago.
Since the beginning of the year it had approved Ecu735m (Pounds 580m) in
bank loans and equity investments for eastern Europe.
Mr Attali yesterday gave no indication of how his proposals for structural
changes at the bank would dovetail with the report of the audit committee,
which was appointed last month by the EBRD's directors to look into the
bank's affairs.
At the meeting of the board of governors in April, in the wake of the
disclosures of the bank's high spending on entertainment and decorations, Mr
Attali promised changes in the role of the budget director, temporarily
separating the responsibilities of the budget director from the central
board.
</TEXT>
