<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Bosnia battle kills hundreds: Croat troops flee Moslem
advance and surrender to Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TRAVNIK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUNDREDS of people have been killed in fighting between Moslem and Croat
forces over the central Bosnian town of Travnik, United Nations military
sources said yesterday, Reuter reports from Travnik.
'I believe the number of dead is a matter of hundreds,' one western UN
officer said. 'We don't know the precise figure because we still can't get
in to all the villages.'
The UN military sources said the Moslems had driven the Croats out of
Travnik in fighting over the weekend, and had followed this yesterday by
pushing out some 3,000 Croat civilians.
The Croat military commander in central Bosnia said he had surrendered his
troops to Serb forces to save them and thousands of civilians after a rout
by the Moslems. 'We had no choice but to turn to the Bosnian Serb Republic
and its army to enable us to save the necks of our children, women and
elderly,' Commander Darko Kolenda told Reuter on nearby Mount Vlasic, which
is held by the Serbs. The Croats' homes had been burnt or destroyed and they
were now camped out in the open on a hillside.
The Bosnian Serb army on Mount Vlasic said 1,000 Croat fighters surrendered
to it rather than to the Moslems. The Bosnian Serb defence minister, Mr
Dusan Kovacevic, said the Croat soldiers were accompanied by several
thousand civilians.
Bosnia's Moslem-led government said yesterday it would co-operate with a UN
plan to set up 'safe areas' in Bosnia - but only if these havens were linked
by protected corridors. In a statement issued by the presidency, and
critical of the international attitude towards Bosnia, the government
attached several strings to its co-operation, including the provision of an
'economic environment' around the towns.
It was the ex-Yugoslav republic's first official comment on last Friday's UN
Security Council resolution authorising the use of heavily armed troops and
air power to defend six 'safe areas' - Sarajevo, Gorazde, Zepa, Srebrenica,
Tuzla and Bihac.
</TEXT>
