<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Twelve divided on the future of energy tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC FINANCE ministers last night dealt a severe blow to prospects for an
EC-wide energy tax to fight global warming, which they refused to endorse
after rows about how to share the burden of the levy.
The failure leaves in doubt the EC's ability to fulfil its commitments under
the Rio climate change convention, and marks a reverse for Germany, Denmark,
Italy and the Benelux countries.
They had all but signed up to the tax plan and based their national
programmes for the reduction of carbon dioxide emissions on the assumption
it would become EC law. In March they warned their partners that the
year-end deadline for ratifying the Rio convention could not be met unless
the tax was in place.
They contend that the EC commitment to stabilise CO emissions at 1990 levels
by 2000 is not possible without the EC-wide tax, necessary, moreover, to
avoid distortions in Europe's single market if member states go ahead with
their own eco-taxes.
In the draft endorsement of the tax the current Danish EC presidency failed
to get agreed, it had stressed the competition distortions which would
follow a failure to agree a Community emissions strategy. The UK made clear
yesterday it is still not convinced of the need for a Euro-energy tax and,
along with France, queried the 'burden-sharing' formula which all but the UK
agreed to in April.
In order to win the support of poorer member states, that formula agreed to
take into account levels of economic development and different levels of CO
emissions in distributing the energy tax burden.
Ms Marianne Jelved, the Danish economy minister who chaired yesterday's
meeting, insisted the tax 'is certainly not a project which is dead',
arguing that public pressure and the need to preserve the integrity of the
single market would see it through in the end. The Belgian presidency, which
takes office in July, is planning a joint meeting of finance and environment
ministers for the autumn.
Separately, the ministers agreed in principle yesterday on an Ecu1bn (Pounds
790m) loan for eastern European nations and former Soviet republics to
upgrade safety at their nuclear plants. The loan, to be provided under the
aegis of Euratom, the EC nuclear energy agency, is on top of already
committed EC aid for nuclear safety in the east of Ecu330m, about 60 per
cent of total assistance from the Group of 24 industrialised nations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
