<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Sweden hangs sale sign on banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWEDEN yesterday made a plea to the chairmen of the world's biggest banks to
consider purchasing a Swedish bank. Mrs Anne Wibble, Sweden's finance
minister, told a bankers' meeting: 'If you wish to buy a bank or part of
one, don't hesitate to do so.'
She was speaking at the International Monetary Conference, an annual
gathering of the chairmen of the world's hundred biggest banks.
None of Sweden's big banks is currently owned or controlled by overseas
institutions. Prior to the election of the centre-right government, there
was an effective ban on foreign ownership of them. But Swedish banks have
been suffering huge loan losses over the past couple of years. Two of the
big banks are already controlled by the government and a further three,
including Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken, have applied for government
support.
Mrs Wibble said yesterday that a decision on the scope and form of any
public support for SE Banken, the country's biggest, would probably not be
taken until the autumn. The government said early this year it agreed in
principle to aid the bank, which had losses in 1992 of SKr5.6bn (Pounds
509m) and has non-performing loans totalling almost SKr25bn. SE Banken wants
to conclude a deal with the government by the end of this month, but Mrs
Wibble said it would take beyond that date to conclude a study of the bank's
needs.
The government is apparently adopting a tough stance, anxious not to be
accused of giving SE Banken soft terms.
The first privatisation candidate is set to be Gotabank which has consumed
most of a state guarantee worth SKr10bn following losses of SKr2.4bn last
year. Its healthy assets carry a value of around SKr50bn, but it has
non-performing loans of SKr40bn, most of which the government is likely to
dump into a separate 'bad bank' before privatisation set for early next
year.
</TEXT>
