<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 93 / Mediation fails in BA-Virgin 'dirty tricks' row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER and ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE acrimonious 'dirty tricks' dispute between Virgin Atlantic and British
Airways looked set last night to be decided in court after the collapse of a
mediation attempt by the Civil Aviation Authority.
BA said the main obstacle to a settlement was Virgin's insistence on a
payment of not less than Pounds 9m in compensation. It suggested that the
matter should be settled by impartial arbitration.
Mr Richard Branson, chairman of Virgin, said it now seemed inevitable that
the matter could be decided only in court: 'Once again, at the last moment,
BA have decided to move the goalposts.'
The collapse of talks ends three weeks of meetings held by Mr Christopher
Chataway, chairman of the CAA, with both airlines to try to resolve the
dispute. The CAA said it was disappointed that a deal had proved impossible
in a dispute it considered to be 'potentially harmful to British aviation'.
BA denied reports that it was ready to pay Pounds 9m to settle the claims by
Virgin. It said it had made clear at the start of the discussions initiated
by the CAA that the proposed settlement was worth nothing like that figure
and that BA's board had reaffirmed its stance on Friday.
BA suggested that all Virgin's claims should be submitted to an arbitrator,
except for Pounds 5m involved in a long-running aircraft maintenance dispute
which is already in arbitration.
Mr Robert Ayling, BA's group managing director, said the airline had always
declared its willingness to pay any legitimate claims that Virgin might
have. 'We hope Virgin will accept this simple, direct and obviously fair way
of determining the legitimacy and worth, if any, of its claims.'
In response, Mr Branson said Virgin had expressly entered negotiations on
the basis that BA pay Pounds 9m compensation for the 'dirty tricks' campaign
to lure passengers away by using Virgin's computer data. 'Much hard work and
effort has been expended by the CAA and Virgin in attempting to agree the
outstanding issues. Just at the point of agreeing those issues, BA, without
any reason whatsoever, have once again withdrawn their offer of settlement.'
Last night, Virgin said that it had originally asked for Pounds 13m, but had
agreed on Pounds 9m as a basis for negotiations if BA dropped a 'gagging
clause' that would have stopped Virgin from raising the matter again.
BA says Pounds 9m offer was off agenda, Page 7
</TEXT>
